Over lunch with a documentary producer last month, I kinda unloaded on the =
music and sports nonfiction genre. In many ways, it=E2=80=99s never been be=
tter for fans like me=E2=80=94given the relatively low cost and breakout po=
tential of these projects, there=E2=80=99s a constant and seemingly endless=
 stream of content. At the same time, even my lunch companion agreed, most =
of these participation docs totally suck.

I=E2=80=99ve complained about this before. Thanks to copyright law and the =
requirement that the artist or their family bless the =E2=80=9Csync=E2=80=
=9D of the artist=E2=80=99s music with video, there=E2=80=99s a glut of pur=
e hagiographies, like the recent Apple doc on Billie Eilish, or quasi-docum=
entary =E2=80=9Cseries=E2=80=9D like Hulu=E2=80=99s Jon Bon Jovi opus. Or t=
here=E2=80=99s the selective biography, like the upcoming estate-approved M=
ichael Jackson movie, which paints
the pop star as a victim of the child abuse claims against him, or the new =
Beach Boys doc on Disney+, which glosses over the pretty major story points=
 that Brian Wilson went crazy and the band members started suing each other=
=2E It says something that everyone=20=
loved Netflix=E2=80=99s Beckham because D=
avid and Victoria dared to reveal a tiny bit of unvarnished candor about th=
eir marriage.

That=E2=80=99s why I had super high hopes for the semi-secret, multipart Pr=
ince documentary that filmmaker Ezra Edelman has been working on for more t=
han four years. Yes, the same Edelman who won universal praise and the docu=
mentary feature Oscar for 2016=E2=80=99s mega-ambitious O.J.: Made in Ameri=
ca=E2=80=A6 and has directed nothing else since.

Netflix never officially announced the Prince project, but back in 2018, th=
e streamer cut a deal with the estate of the enigmatic music icon, who died=
 in 2016 of a fentanyl overdose at
age 57. Edelman came on board to replace Ava DuVernay, who was initially at=
tached to direct, and he finished his cut of the film a while back, even ho=
sting a few friends-and-family screenings last year, I=E2=80=99m told. It=
=E2=80=99s said to be the rare example these days of a truly journalistic e=
ndeavor that employs extensive use of the Grammy winner=E2=80=99s music and=
 archival materials. Sounds great, right?

Not great for the Prince estate, executors of which have seen the film and =
aren=E2=80=99t fans. It=E2=80=99s unclear what exactly peeves them=E2=80=94=
my emails to estate lawyer L. Londell McMillan weren=E2=80=99t returned, an=
d reps for Netflix and Edelman declined to comment=E2=80=94but one source i=
nsists it=E2=80=99s not revelations of drug use or sexual stuff. Instead, t=
he estate argues there are things in the film that are inaccurate, I=E2=80=
=99m told, and they=E2=80=99re protective of the famously private Prince. B=
ut Netflix sources believe this is mostly a control issue, and reflects the=
 fact that
the current executors of the estate are different from those who greenlit t=
he project in the first place.

Nine Hours

While Netflix and Edelman maintain final cut of the film, the Netflix deal =
with the estate calls for a six-hour series, and Edelman delivered nine hou=
rs. The estate has been using that violation of the agreement to essentiall=
y hold the film hostage. This has been going on awhile under the radar, and=
 the back-and-forth between Netflix and the estate is ongoing, with two sou=
rces telling me Netflix is confident a compromise can still be worked out. =
But so far, no deal. And no deal means no Prince movie.

A huge bummer, but this situation wasn=E2=80=99t entirely unforeseeable. O.=
J.: Made in America, which was originally commissioned as a five-hour, thre=
e-part installment of ESPN=E2=80=99s 30 for 30 series, eventually clocked i=
n at nearly eight hours. It=E2=80=99s still the longest film to ever win an=
 Oscar (no, Netflix=E2=80=99s The
Power of the Dog just felt like it was eight hours), and it caused the Acad=
emy to ban =E2=80=9Cmultipart or limited series=E2=80=9D films from future =
consideration. Edelman is said to be as unrelenting in his independence as =
he is meticulous in his filmmaking, so he=E2=80=99s not interested in a tru=
ncated version of the Prince project.

The estate of Prince, who died without a will, also sounds like a nightmare=
 to deal with for Netflix=E2=80=99s unscripted chief Brandon Riegg, documen=
tary leader Adam Del Deo, and the Netflix lawyers. Riegg inherited this pro=
ject from former docs chief Lisa Nishimura. And two years ago, a Minnesota =
probate settlement divided Prince=E2=80=99s estate in two: Prince=E2=80=99s=
 family and friends created Prince Legacy, on the one hand, and on the othe=
r, there=E2=80=99s Prince OAT Holdings, an arm of the rights management com=
pany Primary Wave Music. (Its president, Larry Mestel, did not return my em=
ail.)

Since the two
entities manage the estate together, both must agree on most big decisions =
related to Prince=E2=80=99s intellectual property. Nightmare. Further compl=
icating matters, members of Prince Legacy sued four of his other relatives =
earlier this year over claims they=E2=80=99re wrongfully trying to seize co=
ntrol of the entity. That suit was filed by McMillan, who owns a stake in P=
rince Legacy. Not surprisingly, some of the Prince people are said to care =
about certain things in the documentary, while others care about other stuf=
f.

A legal mess, but can it be resolved? I hope so. One could argue that nine =
episodes on Prince is too many. To be honest, most of these multipart docum=
entary series would be well-served by a Harvey Scissorhands editor. Even Sh=
owtime=E2=80=99s highly regarded 2013 doc History of The Eagles was able to=
 tell the story of the famously dysfunctional band in just two, 90-minute e=
pisodes. And despite his place in music history, Prince as a story probably
isn=E2=80=99t as interesting as O.J. There=E2=80=99s no true crime intrigue=
=E2=80=94we all know how Prince died=E2=80=94and it=E2=80=99s hard to point=
 to many music docs that have been massive hits. Maybe the estate is right =
and Prince doesn=E2=80=99t justify such an extended treatment.

But Edelman is the X factor here, having taken the most worked-over tabloid=
 figure, O.J. Simpson, and turned Made in America into a springboard for se=
aring cultural analysis. Given his track record as a director, it would be =
tragic if he=E2=80=99s forced to shelve this film, even if his ultimate vis=
ion doesn=E2=80=99t match the framework that was agreed upon. You=E2=80=99d=
 think the friends and family of Prince, who, during his life, famously def=
ied industry rules and charted his own creative path, would be sympathetic =
to that argument.

